{"title_page": "The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Kenya", "text_new": "'''The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church) in Kenya''' reported 14,591 members in two [[Stake (Latter Day Saints)|stakes]], six [[District (Latter Day Saints)|districts]], 54 congregations (thirteen [[Ward (LDS Church)|wards]] and 41 [[Ward (LDS Church)#Branch|branches]]), and one [[Mission (LDS Church)|mission]], in [[Kenya]], as of December 31, 2019.<ref>{{citation |url= https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/facts-and-statistics/country/kenya  |title= Facts and Statistics: Statistics by Country: Kenya  |work= Newsroom |publisher= LDS Church |date= 31 December 2018 |accessdate= 2019-04-25 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url= https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2010-01-29/country-information-kenya-34934 |title= Country information: Kenya |work= [[Church News]] Online Almanac |publisher= [[Deseret News]] |date= 1 February 2010 |accessdate= 2013-03-09 }}</ref> On April 2, 2017, church president [[Thomas S. Monson]] announced that a [[Temple (LDS Church)|temple]] would be built in Nairobi.<ref name=\"mormonnewsroom\">{{cite news |url= https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/article/five-new-mormon-temples-april-2017 |title= President Monson Announces Five New Temples: Mormon temples to be built in South America, Africa, Philippines and US |work= Newsroom |publisher= [[LDS Church]] |date= 2017-04-02 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first Kenyans baptized into the LDS Church in Kenya were the family of Elizaphan and Ebisiba Osaka, who were baptized in 1979. The first [[LDS missionaries]] began serving in Kenya in 1980. There was only one LDS missionary couple from then until 1989, when the couple was withdrawn.  [[Joseph W. Sitati]], who joined the LDS Church along with his family in 1985, was designated the lead elder of the church in Kenya at that point.  In February 1991, he met with [[Daniel arap Moi]], president of Kenya. Later that month the attorney general of Kenya gave Sitati and a few other church leaders a form signifying the church was officially recognized.\n\nIn July 1991, the Kenya Nairobi [[Mission (LDS Church)|Mission]] was organized, with Larry King Brown as [[mission president|president]].  The first LDS meeting house was completed in Nairobi in 1994. In 2001 a stake was organized, with Sitati [[Calling (LDS Church)|called]] as [[stake president|president]].  Sitati later became the first [[general authority]] from Kenya.<ref>Church News, 2010 Edition, p. 514-515</ref>\n\n===Membership history===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!width=\"50\"|Year\n!width=\"50\"|Membership<ref>{{citation |url= https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2010-01-29/country-information-kenya-34934 |title= Country information: Kenya |work= [[Deseret News]] Church Almanac (multiple almanacs from various years) |publisher= [[Deseret News]] }}</ref>\n|-\n|1989 || 300{{note label|Note2|b|b}}\n|-\n|1995 || 2,200{{note label|Note2|b|b}}\n|-\n|1999 || 4,039{{note label|Note3|c|c}}\n|-\n|2004 || 6,832{{note label|Note3|c|c}}\n|-\n|2009 || 8,416{{note label|Note1|a|a}}\n|-\n|2012 || 10,922{{note label|Note1|a|a}}\n|}\n*{{note label|Note1|a|a}} Actual Membership for January 1 of the respective year\n*{{note label|Note2|b|b}} Estimated membership for Dec 31 of the respective year\n*{{note label|Note3|c|c}} Actual Membership for Dec 31 of the respective year\n\n==Stake and districts==\n[[File:The Plan of Salvation swahili.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The [[Plan of salvation (Latter Day Saints)|Plan of salvation]] in [[Swahili language|Swahili]].]]\n* Chyulu Kenya District\n* Eldoret Kenya District\n* Mombasa Kenya District\n* Kilungu Hills Kenya District\n* Kisumu Kenya District\n* Kitale Kenya District\n* Nairobi Kenya East Stake\n* Nairobi Kenya West Stake\n\n==Mission==\n*[[Kenya]] [[Nairobi]] Mission\n\n==Temple==\nOn April 2, 2017, Thomas S. Monson announced the intent to construct the Nairobi Kenya Temple in the church's [[General Conference (LDS Church)|general conference]].\n\n{{LDS Temple list top}}\n{{LDS Temple/Nairobi Kenya Temple | format = LDS Temple list }}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LDS Church}}\n* [[Religion in Kenya]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://africasoutheast.churchofjesuschrist.org The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints] Africa Southeast site\n*[https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/?lang=eng The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints] Official site\n*[https://churchofjesuschristtemples.org/nairobi-kenya-temple/ Nairobi Kenya Temple] at ChurchofJesusChristTemples.org\n\n{{LDS-Africa|show}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Kenya, The}}\n[[Category:Churches in Kenya]]\n[[Category:The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Africa]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Kenya]]\n\n\n{{LDS-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Kenya''' reported 14,591 members in two [[Stake (Latter Day Saints)|stakes]], six [[District (Latter Day Saints)|districts]], 54 congregations (thirteen [[Ward (LDS Church)|wards]] and 41 [[Ward (LDS Church)#Branch|branches]]), and one [[Mission (LDS Church)|mission]], in [[Kenya]], as of December 31, 2019.<ref>{{citation |url= https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/facts-and-statistics/country/kenya  |title= Facts and Statistics: Statistics by Country: Kenya  |work= Newsroom |publisher= LDS Church |date= 31 December 2018 |accessdate= 2019-04-25 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url= https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2010-01-29/country-information-kenya-34934 |title= Country information: Kenya |work= [[Church News]] Online Almanac |publisher= [[Deseret News]] |date= 1 February 2010 |accessdate= 2013-03-09 }}</ref> On April 2, 2017, church president [[Thomas S. Monson]] announced that a [[Temple (LDS Church)|temple]] would be built in Nairobi.<ref name=\"mormonnewsroom\">{{cite news |url= https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/article/five-new-mormon-temples-april-2017 |title= President Monson Announces Five New Temples: Mormon temples to be built in South America, Africa, Philippines and US |work= Newsroom |publisher= [[LDS Church]] |date= 2017-04-02 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first Kenyans baptized into the LDS Church in Kenya were the family of Elizaphan and Ebisiba Osaka, who were baptized in 1979. The first [[LDS missionaries]] began serving in Kenya in 1980. There was only one LDS missionary couple from then until 1989, when the missionary couple was withdrawn.  [[Joseph W. Sitati]], who had joined the LDS Church along with his family in 1985, was designated the lead elder of the church in Kenya at that point.  In February 1991, he met with [[Daniel arap Moi]], president of Kenya. Later that month the attorney general of Kenya gave Sitati and a few other church leaders a form signifying the church was officially recognized.\n\nIn July 1991, the Kenya Nairobi [[Mission (LDS Church)|Mission]] was organized, with Larry King Brown as [[mission president|president]].  The first LDS meeting house was completed in Nairobi in 1994. In 2001 a stake was organized, with Sitati [[Calling (LDS Church)|called]] as [[stake president|president]].  Sitati later became the first [[general authority]] from Kenya.<ref>Church News, 2010 Edition, p. 514-515</ref>\n\n===Membership history===\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!width=\"50\"|Year\n!width=\"50\"|Membership<ref>{{citation |url= https://www.thechurchnews.com/archive/2010-01-29/country-information-kenya-34934 |title= Country information: Kenya |work= [[Deseret News]] Church Almanac (multiple almanacs from various years) |publisher= [[Deseret News]] }}</ref>\n|-\n|1989 || 300{{note label|Note2|b|b}}\n|-\n|1995 || 2,200{{note label|Note2|b|b}}\n|-\n|1999 || 4,039{{note label|Note3|c|c}}\n|-\n|2004 || 6,832{{note label|Note3|c|c}}\n|-\n|2009 || 8,416{{note label|Note1|a|a}}\n|-\n|2012 || 10,922{{note label|Note1|a|a}}\n|}\n*{{note label|Note1|a|a}} Actual Membershi